    "type": "ContextOfUse",
    "name": "COU1: Non-cannulated construct compression-bending prediction",
    "description": "FEA predicts construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw design under ASTM F1717 static compression-bending. Validated by direct comparison to bench testing (N=11 constructs across two laboratories). Model influence MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence MEDIUM (pedicle screw fracture leads to revision surgery, not death).",
    "intendedUse": "Demonstrate that the FEA modeling framework reproduces experimental compression-bending behavior of a non-cannulated pedicle screw construct within pre-established acceptance bounds (<10% QoI difference, E/uval < 1.96).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "decisionConsequence": "Medium",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "hasApplicabilityConstraint": {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/cou/cou1-noncannulated/applicability-constraint",
      "type": "ApplicabilityConstraint",
      "name": "Non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw, ASTM F1717 static loading only",
      "description": "This COU applies exclusively to non-cannulated pedicle screws with nominal outer diameter 7.5 mm ± 0.05 mm and thread pitch 2.75 mm, implanted in the ASTM F1717 polyethylene block fixture. The constraint excludes cannulated variants, screws with outer diameter outside [7.45, 7.55] mm, dynamic or fatigue loading regimes, and in vivo or cadaveric test configurations. The FEA ensemble has been validated only for the static compression-bending load case; extrapolation to torsional or axial pull-out loading is not supported."
    },
    "hasOperatingEnvelope": {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/cou/cou1-noncannulated/operating-envelope",
      "type": "OperatingEnvelope",
      "name": "ASTM F1717 static compression-bending operating envelope",
      "description": "Applied axial compressive load: 0–3500 N at crosshead displacement rate 5 ± 0.5 mm/min. Bending moment arm: 44.45 mm (ASTM F1717 standard fixture geometry). Ambient temperature: 23 ± 2 °C. Polyethylene block density: 0.945 ± 0.005 g/cm³. Screw insertion torque: 8.0 ± 0.5 N·m. Rod diameter: 5.5 mm cobalt-chromium alloy, modulus 210 ± 5 GPa. All boundary conditions are held constant within these ranges; deviations beyond ±10% of nominal values require re-assessment of model applicability."
    }
  },
  "hasSensitivityAnalysisObject": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/sensitivity/cou1-noncannulated-sa",
    "type": "SensitivityAnalysis",
    "name": "One-at-a-time and Monte Carlo sensitivity analysis for non-cannulated pedicle screw FEA",
    "description": "A two-phase sensitivity analysis was performed. Phase 1 used one-at-a-time (OAT) perturbation of 11 input parameters (screw Young's modulus ±5%, rod modulus ±3%, polyethylene block modulus ±8%, screw outer diameter ±0.05 mm, friction coefficient at screw-rod interface ±0.05, mesh element size ±20%, crosshead displacement rate ±10%, bending moment arm ±1 mm, insertion torque ±0.5 N·m, rod diameter ±0.1 mm, and contact stiffness penalty factor ±15%) to rank parameter influence on three QoIs: construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement. Phase 2 used Latin Hypercube Sampling (n=1024 runs) with all 11 parameters varied simultaneously using their measured uncertainty distributions to generate Sobol total-effect indices. Dominant factors were polyethylene block modulus (Sobol S_T = 0.41 for stiffness QoI) and screw outer diameter (S_T = 0.29 for yield force QoI); friction coefficient contributed S_T < 0.05 across all three QoIs and was classified as non-influential. The 95th-percentile prediction interval across all 1024 LHS runs remained within ±8.3% of the experimental mean for all three QoIs, confirming that parametric uncertainty does not challenge the <10% acceptance bound."
  },
